WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:06.586 --> 00:00:10.214
Elections— often called
the cornerstone of democracy—

00:00:10.214 --> 00:00:15.470
are tools that ensure a nation's citizens
all have an equal political voice.

00:00:15.678 --> 00:00:20.933
But these so-called “great equalizers”
have long been plagued by corruption,

00:00:20.933 --> 00:00:24.145
partisan divides, and uninformed voters.

00:00:24.395 --> 00:00:28.941
Which is why some of democracy’s first
and most famous practitioners

00:00:28.941 --> 00:00:31.235
used a different approach.

00:00:31.861 --> 00:00:35.406
From 508 to 322 BCE,

00:00:35.531 --> 00:00:40.119
Athens increasingly moved away
from elected officials.

00:00:40.203 --> 00:00:42.580
Outside specialized positions

00:00:42.580 --> 00:00:46.417
like military generals
and senior finance officers,

00:00:46.459 --> 00:00:50.254
most legislative, executive,
and judicial roles

00:00:50.254 --> 00:00:52.799
were appointed via lottery.

00:00:53.132 --> 00:00:58.054
Starting at age 30, citizens could place
a token with their name

00:00:58.179 --> 00:01:00.223
into an allotment machine.

00:01:00.556 --> 00:01:04.602
These machines appointed citizens
to government positions

00:01:04.644 --> 00:01:10.525
through a process designed to ensure
randomness and prevent fraud.

00:01:11.275 --> 00:01:16.531
Before getting the job, chosen candidates
underwent a public examination

00:01:16.531 --> 00:01:18.407
to investigate their character,

00:01:18.616 --> 00:01:22.787
and those that passed would typically
serve for a single year.

00:01:23.121 --> 00:01:24.580
When their term ended,

00:01:24.580 --> 00:01:28.960
they underwent another public review
to investigate their conduct

00:01:28.960 --> 00:01:31.838
and financial dealings while in office.

00:01:32.588 --> 00:01:35.383
This system was called sortition,

00:01:35.383 --> 00:01:38.970
and its goal was to promote
political equality.

00:01:39.220 --> 00:01:44.308
In fact, Athenians saw lotteries
as more democratic than voting,

00:01:44.517 --> 00:01:48.688
since they believed elections
favored the wealthy and well-connected.

00:01:49.105 --> 00:01:51.858
Random appointees, on the other hand,

00:01:52.024 --> 00:01:56.112
were ordinary citizens stepping
up to fulfill their civic duty.

00:01:56.404 --> 00:02:00.366
And since most offices
didn't allow repeat terms,

00:02:00.491 --> 00:02:05.121
sortition prevented people from gaining
too much political influence.

00:02:05.663 --> 00:02:08.666
Of course, this system
was far from perfect.

00:02:08.916 --> 00:02:13.171
Athenian sortition excluded women,
foreign-born residents,

00:02:13.171 --> 00:02:14.839
and enslaved peoples.

00:02:15.173 --> 00:02:19.093
And, as philosophers like Plato
and Aristotle pointed out,

00:02:19.260 --> 00:02:22.930
political decision-making
requires expertise,

00:02:23.222 --> 00:02:27.226
a quality that's difficult
to develop in short appointments,

00:02:27.435 --> 00:02:30.855
and can't be guaranteed
by random selection.

00:02:31.898 --> 00:02:37.028
But broadly, this lottery-based system
had strong public support.

00:02:37.236 --> 00:02:41.908
It was the dominant form of democracy
during Athens’ Golden Age,

00:02:42.074 --> 00:02:48.372
and it only truly ended when Athens’
conquerors abolished democracy altogether.

00:02:48.915 --> 00:02:54.295
So if sortition provided stability then,
could it do so now?

00:02:54.921 --> 00:02:58.507
Political philosopher
Alex Guerrero thinks it could,

00:02:58.549 --> 00:03:03.095
and he’s even proposed a modern
American version of sortition

00:03:03.095 --> 00:03:05.514
that he calls lottocracy.

00:03:05.848 --> 00:03:10.728
Here’s how it works: rather than relying
on one decision-making body

00:03:10.728 --> 00:03:12.313
for every issue,

00:03:12.313 --> 00:03:19.111
Guerrero proposes multiple assemblies,
each dedicated to a specific policy area.

00:03:19.612 --> 00:03:24.700
These single-issue, lottery-selected
legislatures, or SILLs,

00:03:24.825 --> 00:03:28.829
are made up of hundreds
of randomly chosen citizens

00:03:28.829 --> 00:03:34.293
who get trained in their assembly’s
topic area by experts and advocates.

00:03:34.961 --> 00:03:38.756
Then, after consulting with the public
to get their perspective,

00:03:38.923 --> 00:03:44.220
the members of a SILL draft and vote
on topic-specific policies.

00:03:44.971 --> 00:03:47.848
This system extends
all the way to the top,

00:03:47.848 --> 00:03:50.851
distributing even the powers
of the presidency

00:03:50.851 --> 00:03:54.981
across a network lottery-filled
Executive Assemblies

00:03:55.147 --> 00:03:58.025
and the administrative officials
they appoint.

00:03:58.734 --> 00:04:04.240
Advocates of lottocracy believe it could
address three of the biggest problems

00:04:04.240 --> 00:04:06.033
facing modern democracies.

00:04:06.158 --> 00:04:08.619
First, unequal representation.

00:04:09.036 --> 00:04:13.791
Since successful election campaigns
require money and influence,

00:04:13.958 --> 00:04:18.504
many elected officials are much
wealthier than the average voter.

00:04:19.005 --> 00:04:22.717
At various points from 2014 to 2025,

00:04:22.967 --> 00:04:26.762
half of US Congress members
were millionaires.

00:04:27.596 --> 00:04:31.517
Problem two: most candidates rely
on donations

00:04:31.517 --> 00:04:35.730
from individuals, corporations,
and special interest groups

00:04:35.855 --> 00:04:38.357
who may try to influence their policies.

00:04:38.983 --> 00:04:44.071
Lottocracy makes influence harder
to buy by avoiding elections,

00:04:44.280 --> 00:04:50.036
offering appointees generous compensation,
and enforcing shorter term limits.

00:04:50.745 --> 00:04:54.957
The third problem is a lack
of policy making competence.

00:04:55.249 --> 00:04:59.670
While career politicians juggle dozens
of policy proposals

00:04:59.670 --> 00:05:01.964
on countless complicated issues,

00:05:02.173 --> 00:05:06.677
SILLs let their members
become experts in a single topic.

00:05:07.386 --> 00:05:11.140
As you would expect,
this radical proposal has critics.

00:05:11.515 --> 00:05:15.811
Political theorists Cristina LaFont
and Nadia Urbinati

00:05:15.811 --> 00:05:20.149
argue that lottocracy
asks most citizens to defer

00:05:20.149 --> 00:05:22.401
to a randomly chosen few.

00:05:22.818 --> 00:05:26.155
They believe that democracies
should allow citizens

00:05:26.155 --> 00:05:31.452
to exercise political freedom as equals—
and elections are central to that.

00:05:31.869 --> 00:05:34.914
Elections let people
set the political agenda,

00:05:34.914 --> 00:05:39.502
and they bind officeholders
to a continuing cycle of accountability,

00:05:39.668 --> 00:05:42.713
both at the polls and in the public eye.

00:05:43.214 --> 00:05:49.178
In their view, voting is how citizens
collectively shape and limit public power,

00:05:49.303 --> 00:05:50.346
And without it,

00:05:50.346 --> 00:05:53.349
even the most competent
lottocratic government

00:05:53.474 --> 00:05:55.893
could feel like rule by experts.

00:05:56.477 --> 00:06:00.981
Without elections, it can be hard
to say what makes a system democratic.

00:06:00.981 --> 00:06:03.818
But this debate highlights a shared goal:

00:06:04.360 --> 00:06:10.157
we all want institutions that serve
everyone and address real problems.

00:06:10.324 --> 00:06:13.160
And just like every other
element of democracy,

00:06:13.160 --> 00:06:17.498
it’s up to us to keep experimenting
until we find a system

00:06:17.498 --> 00:06:19.417
that achieves those ideals.

